+## Recursive Strategy Contract
+
+The recursive Fibonacci strategy should expose one small public function:
+
+- `recursive_fibonacci(n: int) -> int`
+
+Contract for this function:
+
+- accept one requested Fibonacci position as its only public input
+- return a single integer representing the Fibonacci value at that position
+- treat `0` as returning `0`
+- treat `1` as returning `1`
+- treat larger valid inputs as the sum of the two preceding Fibonacci values
+
+Validation expectations:
+
+- the public function should call the shared validation helper before any recursive work begins
+- the shared helper should own normalization and invalid-input exceptions so recursive and iterative strategies stay consistent
+- the recursive step logic should work only with the validated integer returned by that helper
+- recursive calls inside the unit should not repeat public validation on every branch
+
+Design boundary for readability and testing:
+
+- keep the public contract limited to calculation and return value only
+- keep printing, formatting, comparison, and visualization concerns outside this unit
+- if a private helper is introduced for recursion, it should assume the input is already validated and remain inaccessible outside the module
+
